04256nam a22006015i 9780889208469DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892084697 a10.51644/97808892084692doi  a(DE-B1597)667691  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1027 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a971.42231 aCzernis, Loretta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWeaving a Canadian Allegory :bAnonymous Writing, Personal Reading /cLoretta Czernis. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tNews about Canada, the Uncountry -- tConcerning Contexture -- tReading and Projection -- tConfederation and the Body of Conflict -- tWriting a Body of Unity: Rewriting "Canada and the Search for Unity" -- tMytho-history to Allegory: Tomorrow's Unity as Patriot's Progress -- tMisreading Nietzsche, Rewriting Bloom -- tAfterword -- tOutlining The Report of the Task Force on Canadian Unity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLoretta Czernis applies her sociological training in document analysis to study one government prescription for what ails Canadians. The Report of the Task Force on Canadian Unity rewrote Canada by reinventing patriotism, essentially inviting Canadians to imagine a new Canada. The Report itself is the product of what she calls the “federal writing machine” which exists to continually rewrite and thus reinvent Canada. Czernis’ contextual reading of the Report occurs on two levels: reading technically, she examines the Report’s anonymous writing style that asks readers to imitate its own conclusions (be patriotic, buy a flag, shop at home). Gestural reading invites reading as performance. Canadians are invited to participate in reshaping Canada by reading Canada allegorically, as a social body, capable of changing its form. What a document may intend is not always the same as what is read into it. Mistakes can and do occur in the reading. Czernis suggests that these “mistakes” constitute a significant form of resistance to the anonymous writing machine. Weaving a Canadian Allegory will be of special interest to Canadianists, sociologists and to those involved in cultural, political and textual studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFederal governmentxHistoriographyxCanada. 0aFederal governmentzCanadaxHistoriography. 0aGovernmental investigationsxHistoriographyxCanada. 0aGovernmental investigationszCanadaxHistoriography. 0aHistory. 0aNationalismxHistoriographyxCanada. 0aNationalismzCanadaxHistoriography. 0aTask Force on Canadian Unity. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920846940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208469/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles